snippet.textDisplay: Fountain pen people who are more into collecting inks than pens will often use these to test and swatch their ink collection. Using it with a different kind of ink that is quick drying and doesn't smear would solve your problem. You could look at recommendations for lefty fountain pen users to find those. And fraud-proof inks will even survive watercolor without getting everywhere. ETA: You can also use it for pigments derived from natural sources like tea, if you were so inclined, since you don't have to worry about damage to brush bristles or corrosion of a metal nib.
snippet.textOriginal: Fountain pen people who are more into collecting inks than pens will often use these to test and swatch their ink collection. I use a pretty blue glass pen for more formal correspondence. It'll accept inks with gold flecks, which most fountain pens won't (they clog), so my go-to ink is an indigo with a fine gold fleck that shows beautifully in bright light.

snippet.textDisplay: Just as another like trial and error video, I think it would be pretty cool for you to try string art. This is where you take nails and hammer them into wood in a design you want and then wrap string around the nails to create something. I've always wanted to try so it would be cool to see someone I look up to in the art world try as well.

snippet.textDisplay: The pen is mostly for sketching, not line work or large colour fill in. Should give a go with like a landscape sketch, trees and such, and you'd probably find it to be better. You also need a different paper than regular printer paper. Watercolor paper works great with ink that I've tried.
snippet.textOriginal: The pen is mostly for sketching, not line work or large colour fill in. Should give a go with like a landscape sketch, trees and such, and you'd probably find it to be better. You also need a different paper than regular printer paper. Watercolor paper works great with ink that I've tried.

snippet.textDisplay: Tips for anyone wanting to get one of these- Use water to wash the ink off your pen! It won’t stain your sink, and comes off very easily. And if the ink is running low then just hold the pen vertical. The grooves are so the ink can run down to the tip as you run out of ink.
snippet.textOriginal: Tips for anyone wanting to get one of these- Use water to wash the ink off your pen! It won’t stain your sink, and comes off very easily. And if the ink is running low then just hold the pen vertical. The grooves are so the ink can run down to the tip as you run out of ink.
